<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; CAVE-INS -- Volcanic ash covers the roofs of a
dining room, foreground, and ballroom of a hotel in Subic, Philippines, on
Sunday after tons of ash caused them to collapse earlier.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  US; MILITARY; FACILITY; PHILIPPINES; VOLCANO; SAFETY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  U.S. officials Sunday launched an emergency evacuation to the United States of
about 20,000 military dependents and civilian workers from two strategic bases
after a deadly 36-hour string of eruptions at Mount Pinatubo.;    At least 76
people have been killed since the volcano began erupting June 9 for the first
time in 600 years, the Red Cross said.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. EXPANDS PHILIPPINE EVACUATION
20,000 CIVILIANS SLATED TO LEAVE; THREAT
OF VOLCANIC BLAST DIMINISHES  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Mercury News wire services contributed to this report.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The first 900 of the evacuees boarded <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> warships <DATE>Sunday</DATE> at <LOCATION>Subic Bay
Naval Station</LOCATION> and departed for <ORGANIZATION>Cebu</ORGANIZATION>, a southern Philippine city about 350
miles from <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION>, where they were scheduled to board planes for the <ORGANIZATION>United
States.</ORGANIZATION>;    Even as the evacuation order was issued, Philippine volcano
scientists said that the worst of <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION>'s eruptions may be over,
despite a prediction <DATE>Saturday</DATE> that the volcano was on the verge of a major
explosion.;    The scientists said that much of the pressure built up in the
volcano had dissipated this <DATE>weekend</DATE> in the emission of vast clouds of ash and
rock that turned day to night across the island of <LOCATION>Luzon</LOCATION>, and in a series of
earthquakes, including one that rocked skyscrapers in downtown <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> on
Sunday.;    The ash combined with rain from a tropical storm <DATE>Saturday</DATE> and left
a slippery glaze on buildings and roads as far away as <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION>, about 50 miles
south of the volcano.;    Panicked residents of villages close to the volcano
trudged on foot through knee-deep ash <DATE>Saturday</DATE> to escape the rumbling volcano.
Mudslides washed out bridges, clogged highways and caused hundreds of homes to
collapse.;    The international and domestic airports in the capital remained
closed <DATE>Sunday</DATE> out of concern that the ash would damage jet engines.;    Last
week, the <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION> announced that about 7,000 dependents of military and
civilian workers at the <ORGANIZATION>U.S.-run Clark Air Base</ORGANIZATION> would be evacuated from the
<LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Clark</PERSON>, one of the largest American military
bases outside the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>, is 10 miles east of the volcano and has been
shut down since last Monday.;    <DATE>Sunday</DATE>'s expanded evacuation order includes
all civilian workers at <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and at <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION>, as well as all dependents from
both installations.;    "The only ones left will be uniformed <ORGANIZATION>Army</ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION>,
<ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> or Marine personnel," said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON>Kevin Mukri</PERSON>, a spokesman at <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION>.
"You'll have to be in uniform to stay.";    Workers to remain at <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>;   
Military officials said that about 12,000 uniformed military workers were
stationed at the bases before the volcano erupted, and that most would remain
behind at <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION> while their families and the civilian employees left the
<LOCATION>Philippines.</LOCATION>;    Virtually all of the 16,000 base workers at <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and their
family members were evacuated to <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION> <DATE>last week.</DATE>;    The chief spokesman
at the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Embassy</ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Stanley Schrager</PERSON>, said the evacuation had been
ordered because "it's just untenable to have 30,000 people at <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, double
the ordinary population, especially given the uncertainty over the volcano and
over the future of <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> as to when these people would be able to go home.";  
 On <DATE>Sunday</DATE>, <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> looked like a vast moonscape, with about six inches of
concrete-like volcanic ash covering roads, roofs and runways. Ragged scrubland
and manicured lawns had the same bleak blanket of hard gray crust.;    'A
wasteland';    "Everything looks like a wasteland," said Philippine Brig. Gen.
<PERSON>Leopoldo Acot Jr.</PERSON>, commander of about 150 Philippine troops guarding the
nearly deserted base.;    On <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, volcanic ash and a hail of inch-long
pebbles emitted by <ORGANIZATION>Mount Pinatubo</ORGANIZATION> shut down operations at <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION> and
damaged about 100 buildings, half of them seriously.;    Two people -- a
9-year-old American girl and a Filipino -- were reported killed late <DATE>Saturday</DATE>
when the roof of their shelter at <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION> collapsed under the weight of the
ash.;    "We don't have snow here, and the roofs are not designed to hold
anything," <PERSON>Mukri</PERSON> said. "You get an event like this only about every 600 years.
It's not something you plan for.";    In the city of <LOCATION>Olongapo</LOCATION>, near the <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>
base, eight people were reported killed when the roof of a hospital collapsed
late <DATE>Saturday</DATE> because of ash deposits. Six people died when a church collapsed
in <LOCATION>Dau</LOCATION>, near Clark.;    Readiness unaffected;    <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials said the
evacuation of base workers from <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and Subic would not affect military
readiness in the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION>. All jet fighters had been withdrawn from <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> in
recent months as a result of a global redeployment of forces by the Pentagon.;
   But the volcano is expected to affect the final round of negotiations
between the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> over an extension of the joint
lease for the two bases, which expires in <DATE>September</DATE>. <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials say <PERSON>Clark</PERSON>
may not be able to assume normal operations for months, if not years.;   
There appears to be no similar doubt about the future of <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, which could
reopen fully within the next few weeks.;    Philippine scientists said <DATE>Sunday</DATE>
it appeared that a section of the crater on <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION> had collapsed on
itself, releasing pressure that might otherwise have produced a cataclysmic
avalanche of molten rock.;    Forecast withdrawn;  On <DATE>Saturday</DATE>, the <ORGANIZATION>Philippine
Institute of Volcanology</ORGANIZATION> and Seismology had predicted such an explosion after
obtaining satellite photos showing a nearly two-mile fissure along the
southern edge on the volcano. But <DATE>Sunday</DATE> it withdrew the ominous forecast.;   
The evacuation from <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION> began <DATE>Sunday</DATE> <TIME>afternoon</TIME>, when 900 Americans, mostly
wives and children from <PERSON>Clark</PERSON>, boarded the cruiser <LOCATION>Arkansas</LOCATION> and two frigates,
the <PERSON>Rodney M. Davies</PERSON> and the <PERSON>Kurtz</PERSON>, bound for Cebu.;    Military officials
said the evacuees would probably be flown by chartered jets from the
international airport at <LOCATION>Cebu</LOCATION> to an American air base on <LOCATION>Guam</LOCATION>, and, from
there, to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. Plans to evacuate the Americans by plane from the
<ORGANIZATION>Cubi Point</ORGANIZATION> naval air station, which adjoins <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION>, were foiled by the
ash.;    The aircraft carrier USS <PERSON>Abraham Lincoln</PERSON>, leading a battle group out
of <LOCATION>Okinawa</LOCATION> on the way to the <LOCATION>Persian Gulf</LOCATION>, is to assist in the evacuation,
which is expected to last a week to 10 days, <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials said.  </TEXT>
