operation. The airport is closed to incoming flights.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  VOLCANO; RESULT; US; MILITARY; TRIP  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The U.S. Air Force decided today to withdraw more than 60 percent of its
personnel from the Philippines because of damage to Clark Air Base from the
Mount Pinatubo volcano.;    The decision to withdraw the bulk of the Air Force
personnel suggests that damage to Clark, where they had been stationed, is
extensive and that it may take months before the facility can be used.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  General News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VOLCANO CAUSES MORE TROOPS TO LEAVE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Until today, the evacuation of Americans from the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> affected
primarily military dependents.;    <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION> spewed more ash over <LOCATION>Clark</LOCATION>,
which is 10 miles away, and other areas during five eruptions today, and
regional officials raised the death toll from <DATE>last week</DATE>'s massive explosions
to 227.;    Also today, all flights in and out of <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION>'s airport were
canceled for the day so workers could spread asphalt over tons of ash piled
along the runway shoulders.;    The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> evacuation announcement does not
affect <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Marine Corps</ORGANIZATION> personnel stationed at <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION> naval base 25
miles southwest of the volcano.;    <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Embassy</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Stanley Schrager</PERSON>
said 4,500 <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> personnel will board ships <DATE>Friday</DATE> at <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION> and travel
south to <LOCATION>Cebu</LOCATION>, where they will board flights for the <ORGANIZATION>United States.</ORGANIZATION>;    That
will leave 2,500 airmen in the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> -- 1,500 at <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and another 1,000
at Subic.;    The 1,500 airmen at <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> were left behind to guard the base
when the other 15,000 American soldiers and their families evacuated to <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>
on <DATE>June 10</DATE>, a day after Mount Pinatubo began erupting, ending 600 years of
dormancy.;    The <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military announced on <DATE>Sunday</DATE> that <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> family
members would be evacuated to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and then later expanded the
withdrawal to include families of <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> and defense department civilians as
well.  </TEXT>
