<DESCRIPT>  US; PLANNING; CLOSING; MILITARY; FACILITY; PHILIPPINES  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The United States may give up volcano-damaged Clark Air Base, but it still
wants to keep a military presence in the Philippines, chief U.S. negotiator
Richard Armitage said today.;    As Armitage resumed talks on the future of
Clark Air Base and the Subic Bay Naval Base, his negotiating partner said that
the commander of U.S. forces in the Pacific recommended today that U.S. troops
quit Clark.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  BASE TALKS RESUME; U.S. MAY QUIT CLARK  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The base has suffered extensive damage from the eruption of <LOCATION>Mount
Pinatubo.</LOCATION>;    Foreign Secretary <PERSON>Raul Manglapus</PERSON> said Adm. <PERSON>Charles Larson</PERSON> told
President <PERSON>Corazon Aquino</PERSON> today of his recommendation. The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Embassy</ORGANIZATION> refused
comment.;    <PERSON>Larson</PERSON> visited <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION> during a brief visit that ended
today. The bases' leases expire <DATE>Sept. 16.</DATE>;    The talks were suspended two
months before the volcano began erupting <DATE>June 9</DATE>, forcing the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military to
evacuate more than 17,000 dependents and troops from <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and Subic.;   
<ORGANIZATION>Pinatubo</ORGANIZATION> continued spewing ash today, and scientists fear the onset of the
rainy season will unleash devastating avalanches because of tons of debris on
the volcano's slopes.;    More than 1,000 people fled their homes today
several miles to the north and northeast of <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> to escape volcanic debris,
boulders and uprooted trees washed down a river by heavy rains. Scores more
were ordered evacuated.;    Scientists say the volcano could continue erupting
for up to three years.;    <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials have made it clear that the
continuing threat posed by the volcano leaves the bases' future in doubt. But
<PERSON>Manglapus</PERSON> said <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> may demand even more money to renew the leases.;    Last
month, <PERSON>Manglapus</PERSON> said he would not reduce the compensation demand despite
damage to <PERSON>Clark</PERSON>. He also suggested last week that if <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> wants to
return <PERSON>Clark</PERSON>, it should first clean up the damage from <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION>.  </TEXT>
