<DESCRIPT>  US; PLANNING; REPAIR; VOLCANO; DAMAGE; MILITARY; FACILITY; PHILIPPINES  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The top U.S. commander in the Philippines said today that two bases devastated
by a volcano will be rebuilt and many evacuated dependents might be able to
return next month.;    Meanwhile, Mount Pinatubo rumbled with frequent earth
tremors, spewing ash across a wide area and forcing President Corazon Aquino
to cancel a visit today to a town devastated by the volcano.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  VOLCANO-DEVASTATED BASES TO BE REBUILT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The death toll from nearly three weeks of eruptions rose to 338 as late
casualty reports reached Manila.;    Forecasters predicted strong rain
<DATE>Thursday</DATE> <TIME>night</TIME> near <ORGANIZATION>Clark Air Base</ORGANIZATION> and other areas along the eastern slopes of
the volcano, raising fears of landslides from tons of debris left by the
eruptions.;    Rear Adm. <PERSON>Thomas Mercer</PERSON>, commander of the <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION> naval base,
said that 700 Seabees, or <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION> construction workers, will arrive in <DATE>July</DATE> to
rebuild <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION>Clark Air Base</ORGANIZATION>, which have been heavily damaged during the
last 10 days of eruptions.;    "My mission is to put it back together exactly
the way it was," he said.;    <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION>'s eruption has heavily damaged
both <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and Subic and forced the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military to send more than 17,000
troops and dependents back to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. <PERSON>Mercer</PERSON> said he was hopeful
that many dependents will be able to return next month.  </TEXT>
