<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; DUMP THE BASES -- Demonstrators scatter
volcanic ash from Mount Pinatubo on Monday in front of the U.S. Embassy in
Manila to protest U.S. military bases in the Philippines. The protesters are
symbolically 'dumping' the bases by their gesture.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  VOLCANO; DAMAGE; RELATION; FUTURE; AVIATION; FACILITY; US; PHILIPPINES  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The United States on Monday indicated that it is ready to give up Clark Air
Base, which was devastated by the Philippines' Mount Pinatubo volcano eruption
last month.;    U.S. special negotiator Richard Armitage, arriving for the
latest round of talks on the future of two major U.S. military bases, issued a
statement aimed at preparing Philippine authorities for an American withdrawal
from Clark. The site has been occupied by the U.S. military for most of this
century.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  General News  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. HINTS AT LEAVING AIR BASE
VOLCANO DAMAGE PUTS FUTURE OF CLARK IN DOUBT,
OFFICIAL SAYS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Mount Pinatubo, which continues to spurt huge plumes of volcanic ash, lies
10 miles west of <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and less than 25 miles northeast of <ORGANIZATION>Subic Bay Naval
Base</ORGANIZATION>, a major resupply and ship repair facility. The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> is
interested in holding on to <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, which also was damaged badly by fallen ash
but continues to function as a naval base.;    Citing "substantial damage"
from fallen volcanic ash, aviation hazards from continuing ash emissions and
the threat of further damage from mudflows and floods, <PERSON>Armitage</PERSON> said he had
told <LOCATION>Philippine</LOCATION> Foreign Secretary <PERSON>Raul Manglapus</PERSON> that "the future of <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> is
questionable.";    Other sources close to the talks said <PERSON>Armitage</PERSON> was putting
it mildly. Adm. <PERSON>Charles Larson</PERSON>, the visiting commander of the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Pacific
Command</ORGANIZATION>, told President <PERSON>Corazon Aquino</PERSON> on <DATE>Monday</DATE> that he was "very
pessimistic" about the utility of <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and the adjacent <LOCATION>Crow Valley</LOCATION> aerial
training range, a presidential spokesman said.;    A <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> negotiator said that
although a final decision is pending, the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Air Force</ORGANIZATION> is virtually certain
to give up its huge base 50 miles north of <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION>. Even if the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>
drops its insistence on limiting a new bases agreement to seven years and
accedes to a <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> demand for at least 10 years, the official said, the longer
time frame still would be too short to justify the <MONEY>hundreds of millions of
dollars</MONEY> required to rehabilitate <PERSON>Clark</PERSON>, especially given the uncertainty of
the volcano's behavior for years to come.;    "There is no prospect that
significant sums of money will be spent to clean (<PERSON>Clark</PERSON>) up and reconstruct
it," the official said.;    Most of <PERSON>Clark</PERSON>'s 16,000 Americans -- including
aviators, civilian employees and dependents -- were evacuated in <DATE>June</DATE>, leaving
about 2,200 <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> personnel to guard the base. All serviceable aircraft
also were removed.  </TEXT>
