<HL>
   U.S. Is Seeking
   `Flexible' Pact
   On Clark Base
   ----
   By Eduardo Lachica
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
07/15/91
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
</GV>
<RE>
FAR EAST (FE)
NORTH AMERICA (NME)
PACIFIC RIM (PRM)
PHILIPPINES (RP)
UNITED STATES (US)
</RE>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- The U.S. is seeking a new agreement with the
Philippines that will give it some "flexibility" to use all
or part of Clark Air Base or abandon the heavily
volcano-damaged base entirely, Pentagon spokesman Pete
William said.
   Speaking shortly before the resumption of negotiations in
Manila over the future of U.S. bases in the Philippines, Mr.
Williams said the U.S. definitely wants to keep the Subic Bay
naval base, though. The negotiations were to resume yesterday
for the first time since the eruption of Mount Pinatubo cast
a further cloud on the future of the bases.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   There have been suspicions that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> might abandon the
bases in the wake of the volcano's eruption, especially given
the <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION>'s budget strains and the diminished Soviet
military threat.
   <PERSON>Richard Armitage</PERSON>, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> special negotiator, was
expected to get a damage assessment from Adm. <PERSON>Charles Larsen</PERSON>,
commander in chief of the <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Pacific Command</ORGANIZATION>, before
sitting down with his Philippine counterparts. Before the
talks were suspended, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> had offered the Philippines
<MONEY>$360 million</MONEY> in annual compensation for 10 years. <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> was
holding out for <MONEY>$825 million</MONEY> a year for seven years, but it
was willing to accept a portion of that sum in the form of
trade preferences and other non-budgetary benefits.
   Meanwhile, the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> has to deal with an upheaval of a
political kind. Oscar Orbos, a well-regarded administrator
who helped get the bases talks moving earlier this year, is
out of his job as President <PERSON>Corazon Aquino</PERSON>'s executive
secretary. His abrupt departure last week was linked to
internal politics rather than to his role in the bases
negotiations, but it creates yet another uncertainty about
the talks.
   Opponents of the bases are criticizing the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> for not
doing enough to ease the plight of 250,000 evacuees who lost
their livelihoods when <ORGANIZATION>Mount Pinatubo</ORGANIZATION> covered their farms and
towns with a thick shroud of ash. The <ORGANIZATION>State Department</ORGANIZATION> said
the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> so far has spent <MONEY>$1.6 million</MONEY> in disaster relief for
the affected provinces.
   In a news briefing, <PERSON>Mr. Williams</PERSON> said the Subic naval base
is in "relatively good shape" and isn't likely to be
threatened by mudslides or flooding. However, he said the
outlook for further <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> use of <ORGANIZATION>Clark Air Base</ORGANIZATION> is "very
uncertain" because of the potentially large reconstruction
costs and the hazards that the still-active Pinatubo
continues to pose for aviation.
   Although the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> wants to keep <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, it may decide to
retain just one part of <LOCATION>Clark</LOCATION>, its <ORGANIZATION>Crow Valley</ORGANIZATION> aerial gunnery
range, and give up the rest of the air base, the <ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION>
spokesman said. He declined to say how such a decision would
affect the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> offer.
   Both governments are trying to conclude a new bases accord
by <DATE>Sept. 16</DATE>, a deadline set by a provision of the Philippine
Constitution.
</TEXT>
