<DESCRIPT>  VOLCANO; PHILIPPINES  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Scientists warned people living near Mount Pinatubo to be alert today for
landslides as rain pounded the ash-covered slopes. The 4,795-foot volcano
spewed ash and steam up to six miles high.;    Officials said the death toll
from nearly three weeks of eruptions rose to 338 as the latest casualty
reports reached Manila.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  LANDSLIDE WARNING SOUNDED NEAR VOLCANO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     In a broadcast today over the nationwide <ORGANIZATION>Emergency Broadcast Network</ORGANIZATION>,
<PERSON>Ronaldo Arboleda</PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION>Philippine Institute of Vulcanology</ORGANIZATION> and Seismology
warned that rains have increased the possibility of a deadly lahar -- a huge
mass of mud, boulders and debris -- plunging down the slopes of the volcano.; 
  He said people should be prepared to move quickly away from rivers and
ravines.;    <PERSON>Raymundo Punongbayan</PERSON>, director of the institute, said satellite
photographs showed a new lava dome was forming in the crater, building up
pressure for a possible major eruption.;    He said, however, he did not
expect an eruption on the scale of the one on <DATE>June 14-15</DATE>, which sent ash
drifting as far as <LOCATION>Thailand</LOCATION>, <LOCATION>Cambodia</LOCATION> and Singapore.;    Meanwhile, the
<LOCATION>Philippine</LOCATION> foreign secretary said <DATE>today</DATE> that if <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> decides to keep
volcano-damaged <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION> naval base and <ORGANIZATION>Clark Air Base</ORGANIZATION> it may have to pay
even more for them because "we suffered more than the Americans did.";    The
lease covering <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and Subic expires <DATE>Sept. 16</DATE>, and renewal talks had bogged
down prior to the eruptions over money and the length of the lease.  </TEXT>
