<LP>
   Economists and businessmen say damage to the Philippine
economy from the spectacular eruption of Mt. Pinatubo has
been relatively minimal so far. But they are less certain of
the volcano's effect on the two U.S. military bases that
sprawl in its shadow.
   The Pentagon said the possibility of future eruptions and
the cost of repairs to Clark Air Base and Subic Bay naval
base may force the U.S. to re-evaluate its presence.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   "The question of whether we will remain in the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>
is something we have to look at in light of this disaster,"
<ORGANIZATION>Pentagon</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Pete Williams</PERSON> said.
   Mass evacuations from the slopes of <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION> and
nearby cities and towns and the closure of <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> have created
a sense that the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> faces a disaster similar in
severity to the <DATE>July 1990</DATE> earthquake that killed more than
2,000 people and damaged roads, bridges and buildings
throughout the main island of <LOCATION>Luzon</LOCATION>. But estimates by
Philippine officials, foreign economists and
international-aid experts suggest that the eruption, which
has killed about 170 people, will have little impact on the
country's economy.
   Vulcanologists say the worst of the eruptions are probably
past, and concern in <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> is turning to the future of the
ash-coated <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> bases. The bases have been the subject of
protracted and acrimonious talks that appeared to be moving
toward agreement when Mt. Pinatubo stirred last week after a
600-year sleep.
   <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Embassy</ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON>Stanley Schrager</PERSON> said the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> is
assessing damage at <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION>, and "until we have
that assessment, it's too early to speculate on the future of
the bases or the future of the negotiations." He added that
"no formal policy review" is under way, and that "the talks
have not been suspended or put on hold in that sense."
   Officials in the <ORGANIZATION>Philippine Department of Foreign Affairs</ORGANIZATION>,
which has overseen the base negotiations, expressed concern
that the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> would use the reduced utility of the bases as a
bargaining chip to press for a cut in compensation payments
to <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> or to obtain an extended lease. The <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Embassy</ORGANIZATION>
said the <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> would not exploit the situation.
   The lease on both bases expires <DATE>Sept. 16</DATE>, and <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION>
has offered to pay <MONEY>$360 million</MONEY> a year in bases-linked
compensation, mostly military aid, for an extension of 10 to
12 years. <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> has been demanding <MONEY>$825 million</MONEY> a year in
exchange for a seven-year extension.
   The 4,500 <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Air Force</ORGANIZATION> personnel and 23,000 dependents
and civilians who are being withdrawn from the two bases
would hurt the local economy nearby. But economists believe
the eruption won't further cloud the country's already grim
overall economic prospects, though tourism is likely to
suffer. A <ORGANIZATION>World Bank</ORGANIZATION> economist said its projections for
growth in gross national product of <PERCENT>1.5%</PERCENT> to <PERCENT>2%</PERCENT> this year and
<PERCENT>3.5%</PERCENT> in <DATE>1992</DATE> would remain unchanged.
   While some observers express concern that the eruption
could deter foreign investors, businessmen in <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> are
generally unfazed. "The <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> has come through far
worse than Mount Pinatubo," said <PERSON>Thomas J. Leber</PERSON>, president
of the <ORGANIZATION>American Chamber of Commerce</ORGANIZATION> in the <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
