<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; VOLCANIC BURIAL -- A villager gazes in
bewildered horror at the mud from volcanic debris that buried homes along a
river near Mount Pinatubo.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PHILIPPINES; VOLCANO; DISASTER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  A thundering wall of mud and boulders roared down a river near Mount Pinatubo
on Sunday, burying homes as residents looked on helplessly.;    While there
were no reports of casualties, authorities warned villagers living near the
volcano that they could expect worse mud flows, including huge waves of
volcanic ash and debris capable of entombing whole towns.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  MUD, ROCKS POUR DOWN RIVER NEAR PINATUBO  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The private television station <ORGANIZATION>GMA</ORGANIZATION> said mud flows had occurred near the
towns of <LOCATION>Porac</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Florida Blanca</LOCATION>, about 40 miles northwest of <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> and near
the volcano.;    The <ORGANIZATION>Philippine Institute of Volcanology</ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON>Seismology</PERSON> said
the incidents were not volcanic mud flows, but flooding and landslides caused
by heavy rains and accumulations of mud and volcanic debris from recent
eruptions.;    The institute said the <LOCATION>Porac River</LOCATION> in <LOCATION>Pampanga</LOCATION> had risen three
feet because of rain and ash accumulations since <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION> began erupting
<DATE>June</DATE> 9.;    In the village of Pio, on the <LOCATION>Porac River</LOCATION>, residents fled their
homes near the riverbanks when they heard the rumbling sound.;    Soldiers
fired their weapons in the air to warn residents. Reporters said a huge mound
of steaming earth and boulders as large as refrigerators suddenly rolled down
the banks of the river, burying houses up to their roofs.;    There were no
reports of fatalities since everyone in the village had moved to higher
ground, the reporters said. Officials warned of possible flooding along four
other rivers in <LOCATION>Pampanga</LOCATION>, <PERSON>Tarlac</PERSON> and <LOCATION>Zambales</LOCATION> provinces, which border the
volcano.;    In <LOCATION>Japan</LOCATION>, at least 1,200 people were evacuated from their homes
<DATE>Sunday</DATE> as torrential rains swept down debris from <LOCATION>Mount Unzen</LOCATION>'s previous
eruptions.;    Volcanic ash and basketball-size rocks washed down three rivers
from the 4,485-foot volcano, but no casualties were reported, said <PERSON>Ichiro Otsu</PERSON>
of the fire department in <LOCATION>Shimabara</LOCATION>, at the base of the volcano.;    More than
9,000 residents have been evacuated from outlying parts of <LOCATION>Shimabara</LOCATION>, a city
of 45,000, since avalanches of ash and superheated rocks spewing from the
volcano killed 41 people and injured 10 others <DATE>June 4</DATE>.  </TEXT>
