<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; SAFE -- Susan Stissar, wife of an airman,
plays with a friend's baby Monday as she and her dogs relax at Subic Bay Naval
Base in the Philippines. About 14,500 Americans were evacuated from Clark Air
Base, 48 miles away, after the eruption of Mount Pinatubo.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  PHILIPPINES; VOLCANO; FORECAST; US; MILITARY; FACILITY; ESCAPE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  Carrying enough belongings for three days but enough fears for a lifetime,
about 14,500 Americans fled the U.S.-run Clark Air Base on Monday in the
shadow of a huge volcano belching thick plumes of dark ash and steam.;   
Thousands of cars and vans, loaded with children and canaries, dogs and duffel
bags, inched bumper-to-bumper down a winding two-lane road toward safety at
the giant Subic Bay Naval Base on Luzon's west coast. The 48-mile trip took up
to six hours under a blazing sun, leaving both cars and tempers overheated.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  AIR BASE PERSONNEL TAKE A LONG, HOT DRIVE
TO SAFETY  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See related story page 1A of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     "We're gonna end up like refugees," fumed <ORGANIZATION>Air Force Staff</ORGANIZATION> Sgt. <PERSON>Lenny
Mastri</PERSON>, as he sat in a mileslong traffic jam with his wife and three children.
"I'd rather be back home. I'm not worried about the volcano.";    "When the
<ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> says move, we move," said <PERSON>Devata Rivard</PERSON>, whose husband was one of
1,500 <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> troops left behind to guard <LOCATION>America</LOCATION>'s oldest overseas base. "But I
believe the Lord will take care of us.";    <ORGANIZATION>U.S. Navy</ORGANIZATION> officials at <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION>
will need all the help they can get. The sudden evacuation from a feared
eruption of <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION> has doubled <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION>'s resident population, a base
where housing already is in short supply.;    "We've asked all families to
double up," said Lt. Cmdr. <PERSON>Kevin Mukri</PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION> spokesman. "We're stuffing
people anywhere we can. . . . Basically, anywhere we can put a cot, we are."; 
  Some of the departing <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> personnel feared that "economic intruders,"
official <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> jargon for local thieves, will take advantage of the
Americans' absence.;    "We took everything we wanted to see again," said a
burly <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> sergeant whose red pickup truck was heavily loaded with bags
and boxes. "We live off-base. We think when we get back, everything will be
ripped off.";    A hand-lettered sign for Filipino workers, saying "No Work
Today," was tacked to the front gate at <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> after the last convoy of cars
left. Armed military police sped about inside in jeeps, but the sprawling base
otherwise appeared deserted.;    Not so outside, where some 350,000 residents
of <LOCATION>Angeles City</LOCATION> went about their lives.;    Philippine officials ordered more
than 12,000 Filipinos living near the volcano to leave the mountain, but they
did not evacuate <LOCATION>Angeles City.</LOCATION>;    City police Sgt. <PERSON>Rodolfo Talledo</PERSON> said most
residents were concerned about the volcano but there was no panic.;    "No one
seems to be afraid and nobody is evacuating because they don't think they are
in any immediate danger," he said. "Only the people from <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> left.";    The
departing Americans left behind a town of morose merchants, dispirited tavern
owners and idle bar girls at establishments with names like The Happy <PERSON>Hooker</PERSON>,
The Zoo and, perhaps a bit too apt these days, Earthquake McGoon's.;    Out on
the highway, one vendor did a brisk business selling icy soda pop to the long
line of departing Americans; another hawked bags of potato chips from under a
highway bridge. It seemed an odd start to what appears to be a long, uncertain
<DATE>summer</DATE> for tens of thousands of people forced from their homes by an angry
volcano.;    "The mountain's going to determine how long this is going to
last," said <PERSON>Kenneth West</PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> master sergeant stuck in a
non-air-conditioned car in the steamy traffic jam with his wife and four boys.  </TEXT>
