<DESCRIPT>  US; NUCLEAR; WEAPON; PHILIPPINES; CAMP; PROBE; VOLCANO  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The United States should tell the Philippines whether it stores nuclear
weapons at an air base threatened by a volcano, the chairman of the Philippine
Senate Foreign Relations Committee said today.;    Sen. Leticia Ramos-Shahani
was referring to warnings by an anti-bases activist that radiation
contamination could result if volcanic materials from the erupting Mount
Pinatubo spreads to any nuclear weapons that may be stored at nearby Clark Air
Base.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. URGED TO TELL TRUTH ON NUCLEAR ARMS
AT BASE  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> refuses to say whether it keeps nuclear arms in the
<LOCATION>Philippines.</LOCATION>;    "There must be action because this may be affected by
<ORGANIZATION>Pinatubo</ORGANIZATION>," <PERSON>Shahani</PERSON> said. "This policy of neither confirming nor denying must
be changed. They should remove these nuclear weapons. It is very dangerous
with this (volcano) and I believe it would be OK to change the policy.";    On
<DATE>Monday</DATE>, nearly 15,000 Americans evacuated <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> after <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION>, 10 miles
to the west, began rumbling. The volcano exploded and erupted <DATE>Wednesday</DATE> and
today.;    About 1,500 American security forces stayed behind to guard the
installation, while the rest went to <LOCATION>Subic Bay</LOCATION> naval base, 30 miles southwest
of Pinatubo.;    <PERSON>Shahani</PERSON>, sister of <ORGANIZATION>Defense</ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON>Fidel Ramos</PERSON>, said
diplomatic pressure should be exerted on <LOCATION>Washington</LOCATION> to relax the "no
confirmation" policy. She said she would consult her <ORGANIZATION>Senate</ORGANIZATION> colleagues on the
issue.  </TEXT>
