<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; AT EASE -- A U.S. sailor takes a break after
scooping volcanic ash from rooftops Wednesday at Subic Bay Naval Base.  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  US; REPAIR; PHILIPPINES; MILITARY; FACILITY; VOLCANO; DAMAGE  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The top commander of U.S. forces in the Philippines said Wednesday that the
United States intends to keep two major military bases that have been heavily
damaged by volcanic eruptions and plans to start rebuilding them next month.; 
  "My mission is to put it back together exactly the way it was," Rear Adm.
Thomas Mercer told reporters at Subic Bay Naval Base.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. TO REBUILD DAMAGED BASES IN PHILIPPINES,
COMMANDER SAYS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Mercer, the base's <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> commander, said he hoped that many dependents
evacuated to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> after <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION>'s most powerful eruption
<DATE>June 15</DATE> would be able to return in <LOCATION>July.</LOCATION>;    The optimistic assessment came as
the volcano, about 25 miles northeast of <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION> and 10 miles west of <ORGANIZATION>Clark Air
Base</ORGANIZATION>, continued to spout plumes of ash more than six miles high and rocked the
area with frequent earth tremors.;    More than 330 Filipinos have been
reported killed by the volcanic discharges, most of them crushed in homes and
buildings that collapsed under the weight of falling ash.;    With falling ash
near <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> preventing air operations and expected to continue up to a year or
more, the future of the huge air base is in doubt, diplomats have said.
Dependents of <ORGANIZATION>Air Force</ORGANIZATION> personnel living on or near the base have been sent
back to the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION>. All but about 2,500 of the 7,000 service personnel
assigned there have been evacuated, and the few aircraft that were still based
at <PERSON>Clark</PERSON> have been flown elsewhere.;    At <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, which is considered a more
vital installation, some facilities are operating despite a heavy ash fall.  </TEXT>
