<DESCRIPT>  US; NAVY; END; PHILIPPINES; MILITARY; FACILITY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The Philippines said today that the U.S. Navy will withdraw from Subic Bay
Naval Base by the end of 1992, closing the largest American naval installation
in East Asia and the last American base in this former U.S. colony.;  
President Corazon Aquino's chief aide, Franklin Drilon, made the announcement
at a news conference after he and U.S. Ambassador Frank Wisner failed to iron
out differences, including Manila's ban on nuclear weapons at the facility.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Front  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  U.S. NAVY TO ABANDON SUBIC BAY BY END OF 1992,
PHILIPPINES SAYS  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     "The friendly and cordial relations between the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> and the
<LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> will continue," <PERSON>Drilon</PERSON> said. "Both governments will continue to
build on this strong bond of friendship between the two countries.";   The
announcement ends nearly a century of <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> military presence in this country,
which began when the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> seized the islands from <LOCATION>Spain</LOCATION> in 1898.;  
<ORGANIZATION>Clark Air Base</ORGANIZATION>, the other major <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> installation, was closed last month after
it was damaged by the eruption of <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo.</LOCATION>;   <PERSON>Drilon</PERSON> said there was
nothing to preclude future talks on a longer withdrawal after a new Philippine
government takes office <DATE>June 30.</DATE>;   But <LOCATION>U.S.</LOCATION> officials have indicated that
further talks are unlikely and that they will begin pulling out troops in
strength after the base's three dependent schools close <DATE>June 12.</DATE>;   No
immediate comment was available from Washington.;   The 60,000-acre base 50
miles west of <LOCATION>Manila</LOCATION> has about 5,800 troops and 4,500 dependents.;   Closing
of the base will cost thousands of Filipinos their jobs. Most of the 300,000
residents of <LOCATION>Olongapo</LOCATION>, adjacent to <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, rely on the base for their
livelihood.;   Nearby Zambales province is reeling from the devastating
effects of the <DATE>June</DATE> eruptions of <LOCATION>Mount Pinatubo</LOCATION>, which damaged <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION> and
forced the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> to abandon <ORGANIZATION>Clark Air Base.</ORGANIZATION>;   In <DATE>September</DATE> the
<ORGANIZATION>Philippine Senate</ORGANIZATION> rejected a 10-year lease for <ORGANIZATION>Subic</ORGANIZATION> in return for <MONEY>$203
million</MONEY> in annual aid.;   The <LOCATION>Philippines</LOCATION> insisted the <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> honor
constitutional prohibitions against nuclear weapons on Philippine soil and
also provide a detailed plan for withdrawing.;   The <LOCATION>United States</LOCATION> refuses to
say whether nuclear weapons are stored at <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, although it is widely assumed
that ships calling at the port carry them.;   Philippine officials noted that
President <PERSON>Bush</PERSON> already had pledged to remove tactical nuclear weapons from
surface warships.;   <LOCATION>Subic</LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION>Navy</ORGANIZATION>'s major supply and repair facility in the
western <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION>, provided logistical support for <ORGANIZATION>Seventh Fleet</ORGANIZATION> operations in
the <LOCATION>Pacific</LOCATION> and <LOCATION>Indian Ocean</LOCATION>.  </TEXT>
